 {"id":"bd-1ke","title":"Epic: Integrate rich_rust for Premium Console Output","description":"# Epic: rich_rust Integration for Premium Console Output

## Overview
Integrate the rich_rust library (a Rust port of Python's rich) throughout rust_proxy to transform all console output from basic terminal text into a visually stunning, professional CLI experience.

## Business Justification
- rust_proxy is a developer tool used by both humans and AI coding agents
- Premium visual output increases perceived quality and professionalism
- Better output formatting reduces cognitive load when reading status/diagnostics
- Consistent styling across all commands creates a cohesive product feel

## Critical Constraint: Agent Safety
The PRIMARY users of rust_proxy are AI coding agents (Claude Code, Codex, Gemini). These agents parse CLI output to make decisions. Therefore:
- ALL --json output MUST remain unchanged and machine-parseable
- Piped output (non-TTY) MUST be plain text without ANSI codes
- Environment variables like NO_COLOR, CI, CLAUDE_CODE must be respected
- Rich formatting is ONLY for human-interactive terminal sessions

## Technical Approach
1. Create a centralized OutputDispatcher that detects Human vs Machine mode
2. Define a semantic color theme (success=green, error=red, etc.)
3. Build reusable rich widgets (panels, rules, tables, badges)
4. Update each command to use rich output for Human mode only
5. Preserve existing JSON output paths completely unchanged

## Success Criteria
- All commands show beautiful, colored, formatted output in interactive terminals
- All --json output is byte-for-byte identical to current behavior
- Agents can continue to use rust_proxy without any parsing changes
- Output gracefully degrades on limited terminals (256-color, 16-color, no-color)

## Scope
- ~10 CLI commands to update
- ~4 new source files to create (output module)
- ~8 existing source files to modify
